“I think he can see you.”
“Yes, I am aware.”
“Well then, Mandri, in the spirit of being honest I would like to tell that I don’t actually have a daughter named Lora. Never did. This woman here, her name is Pel. She is a…well,” he turned to this ‘Pel’, and said, “I think you should go ahead and show him.”

dire. There was a nasty squint in the shadow of her shawl, as well as a nose that was impossible to reason with. She wasn’t too old, just sun-leathered, and dammit she was tall, too tall for an old woman. That was man’s air she was breathing.

Mandri figured she was strong too, because her back bore a large canvas sack that nearly doubled her size. And she wasn’t adorned with the usual veneer of civilization—no shine-black bracelets, or bangles, or silver hoop earrings, no makeup or red-thread leaves trimming her robe. The only ornament in sight was the turtle-shell hilt of a dagger that she kept fashionably crooked in her waistband. The rest of her tawny self seemed slapped together in a reed hut on the banks of the river Jek. Her robes were black, yes, but stained dusty brown all over. She was dirty, with perfect teeth, yes, a full complement of perfectly straight and sun-bleached teeth were sparkling. They practically outshone the sun.

 it was hard to tell her mood because the burgeonsight had all her aged lines boiling in a cauldron of witchy weirdness. But there was something in it. She was staring at him too intensely. He was being beheld. Hers were a lovers eyes, or a murderer’s, it was difficult to say because there was a fine line between the two and those irises were wiggling and popping like beans in hot oil.
“What keeps you here?” she asked. “You have nothing. Is it the ox?” She stepped towards Gil and gave him a pat. Gil was awake now. His protuberant eyes were staring blankly off into the horizon.
“No,” said Mandri simply.
“Then you won’t mind if I make a meal of him?”
“Make a what?” 
“You won’t mind if I butcher and eat your ox?”
 Mandri started up, bruising his hip on a root, but he pushed through the ache to firmly declare, “Gil’s not for eating.”
“You named the beast, Gil?”
“I did.”
Gil mooed in recognition. Pel jingled her silver string, prompting Mandri to add, “He’s not for sale either.”
The old witch grimaced and tucked her silver back into her robe. In the same motion, she gripped the turtle-shell hilt at her waist and drew a long, black knife from an unseen sheathe. The sudden sight of this thin, curved blade drew Mandri up, and when she put it against Gil’s neck, he shrieked.
“What are you doing!? Let him be!”
“All things die, child. It is near enough this ox’s time.” With her free hand, she lifted Gil’s head, and she scraped her knife’s edge up and down against Gil’s throat. The poor beast, eager to get in a good scratch, closed his eyes and lifted his chin higher to make sure Pel could scratch the whole length of it.
“If you put one mark on him,” Mandi said, “You will regret it.”
“You would kill me to save your ox?”
“Without hesitation.”
Pel lowered her blade. “That’s not good,” she said. “That is a score against you. If you have the stomach I seek, then you should be free from such attachments. Still, I suspect I can help with that.”
With uncanny speed she cupped Gil’s snout under her arm and reached around his neck with her knife. She plunged her blade into the ox’s flesh, driving it tight up against his jaw, then abruptly yanked it round to the other side.
Gil let out a powerful bellow, deep and pitching. His whole bulk lurched backwards, pulling his head from Pel’s grasp. He bucked as he stood up, knocking her aside, and he hoofed it into the dusty field, bleeding and bleating as he went, though he came to a stop just twenty yards away, blood pouring into the earth, apparently realizing there was nowhere to go. His look back was full of confusion at the betrayal.
Mandri snarled, picked up a rock, and he leaped after the old hag who sat watching with glee.
One sharp elbow into his uglies sent him sprawling to the ground.
“So, you’re not a eunuch,” Pel said with an awful sneer.
Mandri scrambled up to his knees and reached for Pel’s robe, but the cloth seemed to melt between his fingers.
And then he saw something he could not believe.
She flew.
She flew, feet off the dirt, straight like an arrow; she flew towards his dying ox, and once flying, she was nothing but a scowling head and billowing robe, dark eyes alight with bestial rage. The sound of her shriek was borne not from her lungs, but from the deepest depths of Shis.
She plunged head first into Gil’s body, tearing a hole into his belly as easily as if her nose were made of flint. Gil crumpled to the ground, and she went with him, her head and shoulders fixed into his side. And before Gil’s spine had the chance to spasm, she tore herself from his flesh with the neck of his first stomach clenched between her teeth. She spat it out, then ripped the rest of the innards free from their lining. Kneeling, she hugged the largest stomach up to the sun. Her lips uttered a speech as black as Fabled Black. 
Mandri clasped his ears, but he could not look away. He prepared himself for some final gross barbarity, and it came when Pel’s chanting appeared to squeeze a bright speck of light from Gil’s stomach. She sipped this magnificence into her chest through pursed lips, as one might sip a too-hot tea.
Satiated, she dropped Gil’s great stomach onto the dirt.
The tension in her shoulders melted.
Next thing Mandri knew, she was standing above him, her face a withered sponge of blood.
“Time to go,” she growled. “You can bring your drink.”</Text>
